{
  "failure_analysis": "The reduction move (move_fallback_0) timed out in Lean because it attempted to formalize a complex chain of inequalities (Prime Number Theorem, iterated logs, interval-to-gap conversion) in a single large lemma. This overwhelmed the solver (20s limit). Meanwhile, the search got stuck by repeatedly injecting the same generic fallback move 'Construct a CRT covering lemma...' which, while formally verified by Lean, is too abstract to advance the concrete milestones (reduction_gap_to_pn, crt_covering, parameter_growth). The fallback move did not specify which moduli to use, how to choose N, or how to relate the interval length to the target asymptotic expression. The beam search therefore stalled with no novelty or progress toward the asymptotic parameters.",
  "reformulations": [
    "Split the reduction into three separate lemmas: (a) a lemma converting a prime-free interval of length L starting at N+1 into a gap p_{n+1}-p_n > L with n = π(N); (b) a lemma constructing an explicit covering system using primes from a carefully chosen set; (c) a lemma linking the parameters N, L, and n to the required asymptotic expression involving log log n etc.",
    "Avoid formalizing the full Prime Number Theorem in Lean; instead use known asymptotic estimates (e.g., log π(N) ~ log N - log log N) as assumed facts in the environment.",
    "Replace the generic fallback move with concrete construction steps: first choose a set of distinct primes p_i with sum of reciprocals ≈ 1 (but not too large), then assign residues to force all numbers in a long interval to be composite via CRT."
  ],
  "subproblems": [
    {
      "id": "sp_construction_of_moduli",
      "description": "Construct a finite set of distinct primes {q_i} and residues {a_i} such that for any integer x in [0, L-1] there exists some i with x ≡ a_i (mod q_i). The set should be sparse enough that the product Q = ∏ q_i is not too large relative to N, yet L matches the target bound."
    },
    {
      "id": "sp_crt_application",
      "description": "Apply the Chinese Remainder Theorem to find N such that for each modulus q_i, N ≡ -a_i (mod q_i). Then every number in (N, N+L] is divisible by some q_i and is composite (assuming q_i > L)."
    },
    {
      "id": "sp_parameter_growth",
      "description": "Show that with the specific choice of moduli (primes up to some bound), the length L satisfies L > C * log N * log log N * log log log log N / (log log log N)^2, and then convert to the n-domain via n = π(N) ≈ N/log N."
    }
  ],
  "candidate_moves": [
    {
      "move_type": "bridge",
      "claim": "If there exists an integer N and a length L such that every integer in (N, N+L] is composite, then for n = π(N) we have p_{n+1} - p_n > L.",
      "rationale": "This directly translates a prime-free interval into a prime gap, which is the core of the reduction."
    },
    {
      "move_type": "construction",
      "claim": "Let {q_i} be the set of primes up to some bound B, and assign residues a_i = 0 for all i. Then the interval [0, L-1] is covered if L ≤ B, but we need L much larger than B. Instead, use a set of primes with sum of reciprocals close to 1, e.g., primes in [x, x^2] for a suitable x, and assign residues to cover all residues modulo each prime.",
      "rationale": "This provides a concrete construction for the covering system, which is the key combinatorial step."
    },
    {
      "move_type": "asymptotic",
      "claim": "With the covering system constructed from primes in [x, x^2], the length L can be made as large as x^2 / (log x)^2, and the product Q is about exp(x^2 / log x). Choosing x such that log N ~ x^2 / log x gives L ~ log N * log log N * log log log log N / (log log log N)^2.",
      "rationale": "This links the parameters to the desired asymptotic expression, completing the proof."
    }
  ],
  "recommended_next_search_bias": "construction_of_moduli"
}
